SIMPLE: hock
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hock
<hw>Hock</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[So called from
<ets>Hoch</ets>heim, in Germany.]</ety> <def>A Rhenish wine, of a light
yellow color, either sparkling or still. The name is also given
indiscriminately to all Rhenish wines.</def></p>

<p><ent>Hough</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Hock</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hock
<hw>Hock</hw>,

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hock
<hw>Hock</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To disable by cutting
the tendons of the hock; to hamstring; to hough.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pawn; <as>as, to <ex>hock</ex> one's
jewelry</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hock
<hw>Hock</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of having been
pawned; usually preceded by <it>in</it>; <as>as, all her jewelry is in
<ex>hock</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being in debt; <as>as, it took him two
years to get out of <ex>hock</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hockamore</ent>⟦br⟧
